 This setup ensures you can build full-stack apps in VS Code without ever running out of C-Drive disk storage.

   1. Azul Zulu JDK (with JavaFX): [azul.com](https://www.azul.com/downloads/)
   * Action: Select Java 17 or 21 (LTS), Windows, x86 64-bit. Choose the ZIP bundle of the JDK FX. Do not get the standard JDK or MSI. [1, 2] 
   2. Gluon Scene Builder for Windows: [gluonhq.com](https://gluonhq.com/products/scene-builder/)
   * Action: Download the Windows installer. You will change its target path to D: during installation. [3, 4, 5] 
   3. VS Code Extensions (Install within your existing VS Code):
   * Extension Pack for Java: [visualstudio.com](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=vscjava.vscode-java-pack)
      * Spring Boot Extension Pack: [visualstudio.com](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=vmware.vscode-boot-dev-pack) [6, 7] 
   4. Spring Initializr (Web Hub): [spring.io](https://start.spring.io/)
   * Action: Use this link to generate lightweight full-stack templates. [8, 9] 
   5. Zero-Growth Cloud Databases (No local disk expansion):
   * Supabase Database Cloud: supabase.com
      * Neon Serverless PostgreSQL: neon.tech [10] 
  6. Cloud Paywalls & Subscription Gateways:
   * Stripe Developers Hub: stripe.com
      * Paddle Merchant Engine: paddle.com
* SSLCOMMERZ Hub: You can review their developer integration rules at [sslcommerz.com](https://developer.sslcommerz.com/). They provide clear documentation for raw HTTP/REST integrations that map perfectly to Python code.
* AmarPay Sandbox Panel: You can access their developer specifications at amarpay.com. They use highly straightforward JSON payloads that Python handles natively with zero configuration bloat.

   7. Hydraulic Conveyor (Lightweight Installer Packager): hydraulic.dev
   * Action: Download the standalone Windows package to build your final downloadable .exe files.

   📂 E-Drive Folder Structure Blueprint
Create these exact folders on your E: drive right now. This structure isolates all compilers, tools, global caches, and projects to keep your development environment clean and sustainable.

E:\
├── JavaEnv\
│   └── jdk-azulyfx\          <-- Extract the Azul Zulu JDK FX ZIP file here
├── DevTools\
│   ├── SceneBuilder\         <-- Install Gluon Scene Builder into this folder
│   └── Conveyor\             <-- Place your Hydraulic Conveyor compiler files here
├── GlobalCaches\
│   ├── MavenRepository\      <-- Shared folder where all Spring Boot dependencies will sit
│   └── VSCodeJavaData\       <-- All background Java index/metadata logs from VS Code
└── JavaAppa\
    ├── AppOne\               <-- Source files, FXML code, and logic for your first app
    └── AppTwo\               <-- Source files, FXML code, and logic for your second app

⚙️ What goes where and how to configure them:

Step 1: Configure Windows Environment Variables
Windows needs to know your Java compiler is on the D drive, and Git/Maven must be routed there too.
* E:\JavaEnv\jdk-azulyfx: Contains the unzipped Java runtime engine. You must point your Windows Environment Variables (JAVA_HOME) directly to this directory. 
   1. Press the Windows Key, type env, and select Edit the system environment variables. [1] 
   2. Click the Environment Variables... button at the bottom right.
   3. Under System variables (the bottom box), click New...:
   * Variable name: JAVA_HOME
      * Variable value: D:\JavaEnv\jdk-azulyfx
   4. In that same System variables box, scroll down and find the variable named Path, select it, and click Edit....
   5. Click New on the right side and type: D:\JavaEnv\jdk-azulyfx\bin
   6. Click OK on all windows to save. 
   7. Check on VS Code Powershell Terminal: 
 $env:JAVA_HOME="E:\JavaEnv\jdk-azulyfx"
$env:Path="$env:JAVA_HOME\bin;$env:Path"
java -version
openjdk version "21.0.11" 2026-04-21 LTS
OpenJDK Runtime Environment Zulu21.50+19-CA (build 21.0.11+10-LTS)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM Zulu21.50+19-CA (build 21.0.11+10-LTS, mixed mode, sharing)


Step 2: Configure VS Code Global Settings
VS Code’s Java extension automatically creates huge hidden cache folders on your C drive. We must force it to use your D drive cache folder.
* E:\GlobalCaches\VSCodeJavaData: In your VS Code preferences (Ctrl + ,), search for "Java Data Directory" and paste this path. This forces VS Code's indexing engine to generate its workspace metadata here instead of clogging your C-Drive.
   1. Open VS Code.
   2. Open Settings by pressing Ctrl + , (comma).
   3. In the top-right corner of the settings window, click the small Open Settings (JSON) icon (it looks like a file with a tiny arrow turning). This opens your global settings.json file.
   4. Paste the following lines inside the main curly braces { }. Make sure to separate lines with a comma: [3] 

"java.jdt.ls.vmargs": "-XX:+UseParallelGC -XX:GCTimeRatio=4 -XX:AdaptiveSizePolicyWeight=90 -Duser.home=D:/GlobalCaches","java.jdt.ls.java.home": "D:/JavaEnv/jdk-azulyfx","java.sharedRepositories": [
    "D:/GlobalCaches/MavenRepository"
],"maven.terminal.customEnv": [
    {
        "environmentVariable": "MAVEN_OPTS",
        "value": "-Duser.home=D:/GlobalCaches"
    }
]
   5. Save the file (Ctrl + S). This forces the Java extension to generate all workspace metadata inside D:\GlobalCaches\VSCodeJavaData.

Step-3: Configure Maven Global Repository
Whenever you build a Spring Boot app, Maven will try to download gigabytes of dependencies to C:\Users\Username\.m2. We must intercept this.
* E:\GlobalCaches\MavenRepository: The critical storage-saver folder. By sharing this single folder across all your future apps, Maven will only download a Spring Boot library once. AppTwo will completely reuse the libraries downloaded by AppOne instead of downloading duplicate data.

   1. Go to D:\GlobalCaches\MavenRepository.
   2. Inside this folder, create a plain text file using Notepad and name it exactly: settings.xml
   3. Paste this exact configuration block inside it:

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<settings xmlns="http://apache.org"
          xmlns:xsi="http://w3.org"
          xsi:schemaLocation="http://apache.org http://apache.org">
  
  <localRepository>D:/GlobalCaches/MavenRepository</localRepository>

</settings>
   4. Save and close the file.
   5. Important project rule: Every time you generate a Spring Boot project from Spring Initializr and open it in VS Code, you must pass this file to your build terminal. 
   6. When running your app via the terminal, instead of typing ./mvnw spring-boot:run, type: ./mvnw spring-boot:run -s D:\GlobalCaches\MavenRepository\settings.xml

Step 4: Configure Gluon Scene Builder
Scene Builder needs to know where your Azul Zulu JavaFX library lives so it can preview your UI components without downloading separate kits.
* E:\DevTools\SceneBuilder: Holds the UI designer software. Inside VS Code, you will configure your settings to point to the executable file inside this directory so you can open layout designs cleanly. 

   1. Run the Scene Builder installer that you saved to D:\DevTools\SceneBuilder.
   2. Once installed, open Scene Builder.
   3. Go to File -> Preferences (or use Ctrl + ,).
   4. Look for the Java Home or JavaFX SDK settings path.
   5. Set it to point exactly to your portable folder: D:\JavaEnv\jdk-azulyfx

* E:\JavaApps:
- The clean home for your creative assets. Each project folder here will contain small text files (.java logic, .fxml interfaces, .css styling). 
- Because you are hosting your database in the cloud, these folders stay compact and will never uncontrollably grow in size.

Step 5: Route Git/GitHub Caches to D Drive
Git tracking can leave massive hidden index histories inside your user profile on C.

   1. Open your terminal inside VS Code (or Git Bash).
   2. Run these two commands to force Git to look at your D drive for global configurations:
   
   git config --global core.hooksPath D:/GlobalCaches/.githooks

🛡️ The Ultimate Verification Test
To make sure nothing is touching your C drive, open your VS Code terminal and type:
java -version
If configured correctly, the terminal will instantly output Azul Systems, Inc. and display your exact D-drive JDK version. 
Your PC setup is now perfectly isolated, secure, and ready to host infinite full-stack app projects safely on the D drive.

Running Your Secure Terminal Command
Every time you compile or run your Java files on your D Drive to test your connection to SSLCOMMERZ or AmarPay, remember to run the safe terminal configuration string we set up earlier so no hidden target metadata accidentally leaks into your C Drive:

# Navigate to your Java project
cd D:\JavaApps\AppOne
# Run the app safely using your isolated D-Drive repository cache
./mvnw spring-boot:run -s D:\GlobalCaches\MavenRepository\settings.xml

------------------------------
## Next Action Step
With your directories successfully scaffolded, your infrastructure is entirely locked to your D Drive, rendering it immune to storage bloat.

 Initialize a Scaffold Project Template
Conveyor has a built-in feature called scaffold. It generates an optimized, ready-to-run sample desktop app template that doesn't download any bloating framework structures. [1] 
Open your VS Code terminal and run the command matching your preferred language:
## For Java (JavaFX Bundle):
# 1. Move to your Apps directory
cd D:\JavaApps
# 2. Scaffold a pre-configured JavaFX app template
conveyor generate javafx my-paid-java-app

Bridge Conveyor to your VS Code Terminal
Windows needs to recognize the conveyor command when you type it into your VS Code editor.

   1. Press the Windows Key, type env, and click Edit the system environment variables.
   2. Click Environment Variables... at the bottom right.
   3. Under System variables (the bottom box), select the variable named Path and click Edit....
   4. Click New on the right side and paste: D:\DevTools\Conveyor
   5. Click OK on all open windows to lock in the configuration.
   6. Restart VS Code so it updates its system path definitions.

Scaffold Your Bangladeshi Paid App Architecture
Now that the tool is installed globally on your D Drive, you can use your VS Code terminal to generate your production template. Run the command:
# Navigate to your Java project folder
cd D:\JavaApps
# Scaffold a clean JavaFX desktop template
conveyor generate javafx bd-paid-app

Open and Lock down Storage Targets
Open your new project folder (bd-paid-app) inside VS Code. Open the generated conveyor.conf text file and paste these explicit storage-override variables into your configurations to block any automated caching on your C Drive:

app {
  // Keeps all compiling temp structures bound completely to D
  cache-dir = "D:/GlobalCaches/ConveyorCache"
  
  // Explicitly binds the distribution build targets to your local path
  build-dir = "D:/GlobalCaches/ConveyorBuilds"
}

Open and Lock down Storage Targets
Open your new project folder (bd-paid-app) inside VS Code. Open the generated conveyor.conf text file and paste these explicit storage-override variables into your configurations to block any automated caching on your C Drive:

app {
  // Keeps all compiling temp structures bound completely to D
  cache-dir = "D:/GlobalCaches/ConveyorCache"
  
  // Explicitly binds the distribution build targets to your local path
  build-dir = "D:/GlobalCaches/ConveyorBuilds"
}

Open and Inspect the Generated Structure
Look inside your newly created folder (D:\JavaApps\my-paid-java-app or D:\PythonApps\my-paid-python-app). You will see a highly clean structure containing your source code folder and a file named conveyor.conf. [2, 3] 
Open conveyor.conf in VS Code and ensure you modify its build directory targets to protect your C-Drive:

app {
  // Prevent Conveyor from logging build temporary caches on C:
  cache-dir = "D:/GlobalCaches/ConveyorCache"
  
  // Point explicitly to your unzipped Azul Zulu JDK on D
  jvm.runtimes = "D:/JavaEnv/jdk-azulyfx" 
}

------------------------------
## Step 3: Test Run the App Without Packaging
Before you turn the app into a downloadable setup wizard (.exe), you want to test your changes live while you code. Conveyor lets you run the app directly through its own engine using this fast command: [4] 

conveyor run

This launches a desktop application screen immediately. You can now use this window to start rendering your frontend graphics and UI buttons.



The Build and Release Workflow
Once your free-to-browse dashboard layout is written, and your network request to the SSLCOMMERZ/AmarPay API is successfully validating payments, you are ready to compile the final software installer.
Run the local compilation task: [5, 6] 

conveyor make windows-app

Conveyor reads your files, strips out unused operational components using jlink to optimize compression, and outputs a clean Windows installation package directly into the project folder on your D-Drive. Your public users can click this exact file to install your app on their systems. [7, 8] 
------------------------------

To bundle and distribute your app as a downloadable desktop installer using Hydraulic Conveyor, you do not need to install heavy build tools on your computer. Conveyor handles packaging dynamically and includes optimized JVM runtimes automatically.
Follow these steps on the Hydraulic Conveyor website and in your environment to complete your D-drive installation.
------------------------------
## Step 1: Download and Extract Conveyor to your D Drive

   1. Go to https://hydraulic.dev/ and click Get Started or navigate to the User Guide.
   2. Download the Windows standalone package (look for the zip or portable version to avoid C-drive background registry pollution).
   3. Extract the downloaded package directly into your pre-created folder: D:\DevTools\Conveyor\.

------------------------------
## Step 2: Add Conveyor to Windows Path
To run the packaging tool from your VS Code terminal, Windows needs to know its location.

   1. Press the Windows Key, type env, and select Edit the system environment variables.
   2. Click Environment Variables... at the bottom right.
   3. Under System variables (the bottom box), scroll down, select the Path variable, and click Edit....
   4. Click New on the right side and type: D:\DevTools\Conveyor
   5. Click OK on all windows to save.

------------------------------
## Step 3: Create a Minimal Configuration File (conveyor.conf)
You do not use massive software tools to package your app. Conveyor uses a single plain-text config file. Inside your project folder (e.g., D:\JavaApps\PaidAppOne\), create a file named conveyor.conf using VS Code and add these lightweight lines:

// Basic metadata for your Bangladeshi App
app {
  display-name = "My Paid BD App"
  fsname = "my-paid-bd-app"
  vcs = "github"

  // Points to your Azul Zulu JDK FX unzipped folder on D
  jvm {
    gui.main-class = "com.bdapps.paidapp.Main"
  }

  // Forces Conveyor to use your local storage drive for building
  cache-dir = "D:/GlobalCaches/ConveyorCache"
}

------------------------------
## Step 4: Generate Your Executable Installer
When your Python or Java code is finished and ready for the public, open your VS Code terminal and execute the build command:

# Navigate to your application folder
cd D:\JavaApps\PaidAppOne
# Tell Conveyor to package your project into a Windows setup file
conveyor make windows-app

Conveyor will read your code files and generate a single, highly compressed .exe or .msi setup wizard inside your project folder.
Because it uses jlink to strip out unused parts of the Java engine and shares its cache inside D:\GlobalCaches\ConveyorCache, your local disk space remains protected across every application you compile.
------------------------------
To add more dependencies in the future, you never need to re-download anything from the Spring Initializr website. Because you selected a Maven project, you can add new libraries by simply pasting text snippets directly inside your project configuration file.
Here is exactly how to do it in VS Code while keeping your D-Drive storage footprint safe.
------------------------------
## Step 1: Open your pom.xml File [1] 
In your VS Code sidebar, look inside your main project folder (D:\JavaApps\falcon-coaching-center) and open the file named pom.xml. This file acts as the master manifest for your application.
------------------------------
## Step 2: Locate the <dependencies> Section
Scroll down inside pom.xml until you find the block that starts with <dependencies> and ends with </dependencies>. Inside this block, you will see the modules you added earlier (like spring-boot-starter-web and mysql-connector-j). [2] 
------------------------------
## Step 3: Find the Dependency Snippet Online
When you need a new tool (for example, handling JSON validation or encoding security passwords), go to the official Maven Central Repository: mvnrepository.com. [3, 4] 

   1. Search for the library you need.
   2. Click on the version you want.
   3. Copy the XML text block under the Maven tab. It will look like this: [5] 

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.json</groupId>
    <artifactId>json</artifactId>
    <version>20240303</version>
</dependency>

------------------------------
## Step 4: Paste it into VS Code and Save [6] 
Paste that copied text block anywhere inside your <dependencies> block in your pom.xml file. [7] 
As soon as you press Ctrl + S to save the file, VS Code's Java extension will detect the change.
------------------------------
## 🚨 Critical Rule to Protect Your Storage Space!
By default, saving the file causes Maven to try to download the library into your C-Drive. To force it onto your D-Drive, do not let VS Code auto-download it via a popup notification.
Instead, always open your terminal panel and run your isolated refresh command manually:

# Force Maven to fetch the new library strictly into your D-Drive shared cache folder
./mvnw dependency:resolve -s D:\GlobalCaches\MavenRepository\settings.xml

## 💡 Why this keeps you safe across infinite apps:
Because of your shared settings.xml setup, if you add the same dependency to App Two in the future, Maven will see it already exists inside D:\GlobalCaches\MavenRepository. It will link to it instantly in less than a second, using 0 MB of additional disk space on your computer.
------------------------------
